If we read quiescis z· with Gulielmius, we must make the first word disyllabic (see Introd. ii. ξ 15), with its second syllable lengthened ‘in pausa’ (Introd. ii. ξ 33), unless we are to allow elision of -ts before a vowel (Introd. ii. ξ 3); for dierectum is always a quadrisyllable in Plautus, with the first two syllables long. The word is normally joined with i, abt, abin, and the like (recedin Bacch. 579). In illen. 442 we have ducit lembum dierectum. The rhythm would be improved by reading quiu quiesce, i dierectum. But it is quite possible that Plautus here ventured on the unusual expression quin quiescas dierectum? The combination of quin quiescis Ind. with suspende Imperat. need cause no difficulty. Of.
